msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:44
msgid "[b]Note:[/b] In the code example below, I wrote the [code]lerp()[/code] function call across multiple lines for readability. This works exactly the same as writing it on one line."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:49
msgid "Every frame, the code calculates a position somewhere between the turtle and the mouse cursor. The [code]lerp()[/code] function takes care of everything."
msgstr "Co klatkę kod oblicza pozycję gdzieś pomiędzy żółwiem a kursorem myszy. Funkcja \\[code]lerp()\\[/code] zajmuje się wszystkim."

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:50
msgid "It's not the most robust approach for smooth movement, as you'll learn in the future, but it's a helpful function nonetheless."
msgstr "To nie jest najpewniejsze podejście do płynnego ruchu, o czym dowiesz się w przyszłości, ale mimo wszystko jest to przydatna funkcja."

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:49
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Writing a function that returns a value"
msgstr "Pisanie funkcji, która zwraca wartość"

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:63
msgid "You can make [i]your[/i] functions return values."
msgstr "Możesz sprawić, że twoje funkcje będą zwracać wartości."

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:64
msgid "To make a function return a value, you use the [code]return[/code] keyword followed by the value in question."
msgstr "Aby funkcja zwracała wartość, używasz słowa kluczowego [code]return[/code], po którym podajesz wartość, którą chcesz zwrócić."

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:65
msgid "In previous lessons, we had characters walking on grids. For those practices, you were working with cell coordinates like [code]Vector2(0, 0)[/code] or [code]Vector2(2, 1)[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:66
msgid "But cell coordinates are not the same as positions on the screen. A cell coordinate like [code]Vector2(2, 1)[/code] tells us which cell we're in, but not where it is in pixels. To draw something on screen, we need pixel positions."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:67
msgid "We can write a function to convert cell coordinates to pixel positions. Hover over the cells below to see how it works."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:68
msgid "The yellow circle marks the pixel position at the top-left corner of each cell. This corner is the reference point we use for grid position."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:78
msgid "To convert cell coordinates to pixel positions, we multiply the cell coordinates by the size of each cell in pixels."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:79
msgid "For example, if each cell is [code]120[/code] pixels wide and tall, then:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:80
msgid ""
"- Cell [code]Vector2(1, 0)[/code] is at pixel position [code]Vector2(120, 0)[/code].\n"
"- Cell [code]Vector2(2, 1)[/code] would be at [code]Vector2(240, 120)[/code] pixels."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:81
msgid "Use the interactive grid above to visualize the calculations."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:82
msgid "This gives us the top-left corner of each cell, which is the standard way to position things on a grid in games."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:83
msgid "The function below does this calculation and returns the result, so we can store it in a variable or use it right away."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:86
msgid "The [code]return[/code] keyword sends the calculated value back to the code that called the function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:87
msgid "Note: In Godot, we write coordinates as [code]Vector2(x, y)[/code]. The [code]x[/code] value goes left to right (the column), and [code]y[/code] goes top to bottom (the row)."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:88
msgid "In the example below, we call the function and store the returned value in the variable [code]world_position[/code]. Click the run button to see the result."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:96
msgid "Some functions return values, and some do not. You can check this in the documentation panel during practices. When a practice uses specific functions, the panel shows information about them."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:97
msgid "In the documentation, functions that start with the word [code]void[/code] do not return a value. Any other word before the function name means it returns a value of that type. You'll learn more about types in a couple of lessons."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:98
msgid "For now, let's practice returning values from functions!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:96
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Converting coordinates from the grid to the screen"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:96
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Complete the function that converts a cell coordinate to a pixel position on the screen."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:96
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The function takes a [code]Vector2[/code] cell coordinate as an argument, like [code]Vector2(2, 1)[/code]. It should return the pixel position of that cell's top-left corner."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:96
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "To convert, multiply the cell coordinate by the [code]cell_size[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:96
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "We need a function to convert grid coordinates to pixel positions. Complete the function to make the turtle move to the correct cells!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:96
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "To convert a cell coordinate to pixels, multiply the [code]cell[/code] by [code]cell_size[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-22-functions-return-values/lesson.bbcode:96
