#: course/lesson-26-looping-over-dictionaries/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Placing units on the board"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-26-looping-over-dictionaries/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "We have a dictionary named [code]units[/code]. It maps cell positions on the grid to the type of unit at that position."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-26-looping-over-dictionaries/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
#, fuzzy
msgid "Use a for loop to place every unit on the game board. Call the [code]place_unit()[/code] function for each unit. It takes two arguments: first the cell position, then the unit type."
msgstr "Aby to zrobić, wywołaj funkcję \\[code]display\\_item()\\[/code]. Przyjmuje ona dwa argumenty: nazwę przedmiotu i jego ilość."

#: course/lesson-26-looping-over-dictionaries/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "At the start of each battle, units need to appear on the game board. Loop over the dictionary to place them."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-26-looping-over-dictionaries/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "The dictionary keys are cell coordinates. You can use them to access the unit type from the [code]units[/code] dictionary."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-26-looping-over-dictionaries/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Inside the for loop, you can get a unit's type using the syntax [code]units[cell][/code], where [code]cell[/code] is the loop variable you created after the [code]for[/code] keyword."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "Value types"
msgstr "Typy wartości"

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:3
#. TRANSLATORS: The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be
#. translated here
#, fuzzy
msgid "In your code, values have a particular [glossary term=\"type\"]type[/glossary]. You have already learned about several: whole numbers, decimal numbers, strings, 2D vectors, arrays, and dictionaries."
msgstr "W twoim kodzie wartości mają określony \\[i]typ\\[/i]. Poznałeś już kilka z nich: liczby całkowite, liczby dziesiętne, łańcuchy znaków, wektory 2D, tablice i słowniki."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:4
msgid "The computer uses the type of a value to know which operations and functions you can use with them."
msgstr "Komputer wykorzystuje typ wartości, aby wiedzieć, jakie operacje i funkcje można na niej wykonać."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:5
msgid "As a result, it's essential to understand types: they are not fully compatible with one another, and misusing them will cause errors."
msgstr "Dlatego tak ważne jest zrozumienie typów: nie są one w pełni ze sobą kompatybilne, a ich niewłaściwe użycie spowoduje błędy."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:9
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "A prime example"
msgstr "Klasyczny przykład"

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:13
msgid "You want to display the player's health in the interface. Your code tracks health as a whole number, a value of type [code]int[/code] (short for integer)."
msgstr "Chcesz wyświetlić zdrowie gracza w interfejsie. Twój kod śledzi zdrowie jako liczbę całkowitą, czyli wartość typu \\[code]int\\[/code] (skrót od *integer*)."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:19
msgid "However, to display it on the player's screen, the computer wants text: it needs a value of type [code]String[/code]."
msgstr "Jednak aby wyświetlić to na ekranie gracza, komputer potrzebuje tekstu — czyli wartości typu \\[code]String\\[/code]."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:20
msgid "You can concatenate two strings with the [code]+[/code] operator."
msgstr "Możesz łączyć dwa łańcuchy znaków za pomocą operatora \\[code]+\\[/code]."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:23
msgid "So the following code looks like it could work at first glance."
msgstr "Na pierwszy rzut oka poniższy kod wygląda tak, jakby mógł działać."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:27
msgid "But when running the code, we get this strange error."
msgstr "Ale podczas uruchamiania kodu otrzymujemy ten dziwny błąd."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:33
#, fuzzy
msgid "It tells you that you can't add values of type [code]String[/code] and [code]int[/code]: they're incompatible."
msgstr "Komunikat mówi, że nie możesz dodać wartości typu [code]String[/code] i [code]int[/code]: są one niekompatybilne."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:34
msgid "In that case, you need to convert the [code]health[/code] number into a [code]String[/code]."
msgstr "W takim przypadku musisz przekonwertować liczbę [code]health[/code] na [code]String[/code]."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:33
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Converting values into strings"
msgstr "Konwertowanie wartości na łańcuchy znaków"

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:39
msgid "You can get the text representation of a value by calling the [code]str()[/code] function (short for \"string\"). The function returns its argument as a new [code]String[/code]."
msgstr "Możesz uzyskać reprezentację tekstową wartości, wywołując funkcję \\[code]str()\\[/code] (skrót od „string”). Funkcja zwraca swój argument jako nowy \\[code]String\\[/code]."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:40
msgid "You can use this function whenever you want to turn some number or vector into text."
msgstr "Funkcję tę możesz użyć zawsze, gdy chcesz zamienić jakąś liczbę lub wektor na tekst."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:43
msgid "In this case, it turns the number [code]100[/code] into the string [code]\"100\"[/code]. Or whatever number [code]health[/code] is currently."
msgstr "W tym przypadku zamienia liczbę [code]100[/code] na łańcuch znaków [code]\"100\"[/code]. Albo na dowolną inną liczbę, którą aktualnie ma zmienna [code]health[/code]."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:43
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Converting strings into numbers"
msgstr "Konwertowanie ciągów znaków na liczby"

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:49
msgid "You can also convert strings into whole numbers or decimal numbers using respectively the [code]int()[/code] and [code]float()[/code] functions."
msgstr "Możesz też zamieniać ciągi znaków na liczby całkowite lub zmiennoprzecinkowe, używając odpowiednio funkcji [code]int()[/code] i [code]float()[/code]."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:50
msgid "Those functions can convert what the player writes in a text field into a number. For example, the number of potions to sell at once in a shop."
msgstr "Te funkcje mogą przekształcać to, co gracz wpisuje w polu tekstowym, na liczbę. Na przykład liczbę mikstur, które chce sprzedać jednocześnie w sklepie."

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:51
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Some types are partially compatible"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:57
msgid "Most types are incompatible. For example, you can't directly add or multiply an array with a number."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:58
msgid "However, some types are [i]partially[/i] compatible. For example, you can multiply or divide a vector by a number."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:63
msgid "It is possible because other developers defined that operation for you under the hood."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:64
msgid "However, you cannot directly add or subtract a number to a vector. You'll get an error. That's why, in earlier lessons, you had to access the sub-variables of [code]position[/code] to add numbers to them."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:63
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "A surprising result"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:67
msgid "Take the following division: [code]3/2[/code]. What result would you expect to get? [code]1.5[/code]?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:77
msgid "Well, for the computer, the result of [code]3/2[/code] is [code]1[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:78
msgid "Wait, what?!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:79
msgid "That's because, for the computer, the division of two whole numbers should always result in a whole number."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:80
msgid "When you divide decimal numbers instead, you will get a decimal number as a result."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:83
msgid "Even if it's just a [code]0[/code], adding a decimal place tells the computer we want decimal numbers."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:84
msgid "This shows you how mindful you need to be with types. Otherwise, you will get unexpected results. It can get pretty serious: number errors can lead to bugs like controls not working as intended or charging the wrong price to players."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:83
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Understanding and mastering types is a key skill for developers"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:93
msgid "Programming beginners often struggle due to the lack of understanding of types."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:94
msgid "Languages like GDScript hide the types from you by default. As a result, if you don't understand that some are incompatible, you can get stuck when facing type-related errors."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:95
msgid "You'll want to keep that in mind in your learning journey. When writing code, you will need to understand everything that's happening."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:96
msgid "That said, let's practice some type conversions."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:93
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Displaying the player's health and energy"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:93
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "We want to display the player's energy in the user interface."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:93
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Currently, our code has a type error. We're trying to display a whole number while the [code]display_energy()[/code] function expects a string."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:93
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Using the [code]str()[/code] function, clear the type error and make the energy amount display on the interface."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:93
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "You can't change the [code]energy[/code] variable definition: setting it to [code]\"80\"[/code] would break the rest of the game's code. You must convert the value when calling [code]display_energy()[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:93
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "We want to display the player's energy in the interface but face a type error. Use your new knowledge to fix it."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:116
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Letting the player type numbers"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:116
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "In our game's shops, we want to let the player type numbers to select the number of items they want to buy or sell."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:116
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "We need to know the number of items as an [code]int[/code], but the computer reads the player's input as a [code]String[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:116
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Your task is to convert the player's input into numbers for the shop's code to work."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:116
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Using the [code]int()[/code] function, convert the player's input into a whole number and store the result in the [code]item_count[/code] variable."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-27-value-types/lesson.bbcode:116
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "We want the player to choose the number of items they buy or sell in our game's shops. But right now, all we get are type errors."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "Specifying types with type hints"
msgstr "Określanie typów za pomocą wskazówek dotyczących typów"

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:7
msgid "By default, GDScript is what we call a dynamically-typed language. That means that you can just write variables, assign them a value with a number, and assign them another value with a different type."
msgstr "Domyślnie GDScript jest tym, co nazywamy językiem dynamicznie typowanym. Oznacza to, że możesz po prostu zadeklarować zmienne, przypisać im wartość liczbową, a następnie przypisać inną wartość o zupełnie innym typie."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:8
msgid "Unlike in some other languages, in GDScript, the following code is valid."
msgstr "W przeciwieństwie do niektórych innych języków, w GDScript poniższy kod jest prawidłowy."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:11
msgid "But this feature often causes problems down the line. Let's take one example."
msgstr "Ale ta funkcja często powoduje problemy w późniejszym etapie. Weźmy jeden przykład."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:11
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Cell size: decimal number, or 2D vector?"
msgstr "Rozmiar pola: liczba dziesiętna czy wektor 2D?"

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:21
msgid "Games use grids all the time, be it for grid-based gameplay or to make algorithms faster."
msgstr "Gry bardzo często korzystają z siatek — czy to w rozgrywce opartej na polach, czy po to, by przyspieszyć działanie algorytmów."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:22
msgid "When working with grids, you need to convert grid coordinates into positions in the game world all the time. To do so, you give each cell a size in pixels."
msgstr "Pracując z siatkami, musisz nieustannie zamieniać współrzędne siatki na pozycje w świecie gry. Aby to zrobić, nadajesz każdej komórce rozmiar w pikselach."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:23
msgid "You'll likely pick one of two types for that: [code]float[/code] or [code]Vector2[/code], because pixel positions on the screen use [code]Vector2[/code] coordinates."
msgstr "Najpewniej wybierzesz jeden z dwóch typów: \\[code]float\\[/code] lub \\[code]Vector2\\[/code], ponieważ pozycje pikseli na ekranie korzystają ze współrzędnych \\[code]Vector2\\[/code]."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:24
msgid "Either of those two values would be fine:"
msgstr "Każda z tych dwóch wartości będzie w porządku:"

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:25
msgid "Using a [code]Vector2[/code] could simplify some calculations. For example, when converting grid coordinates to game world coordinates."
msgstr "Użycie [code]Vector2[/code] mogłoby uprościć niektóre obliczenia. Na przykład przy konwersji współrzędnych siatki na współrzędne świata gry."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:31
msgid "In this example, because both [code]cell[/code] and [code]cell_size[/code] are [code]Vector2[/code] values, we can add them."
msgstr "W tym przykładzie, ponieważ zarówno [code]cell[/code], jak i [code]cell_size[/code] są wartościami typu [code]Vector2[/code], możemy je do siebie dodać."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:32
msgid "However, if [code]cell_size[/code] is a [code]float[/code], we will get a type error."
msgstr "Jednak jeśli [code]cell\\_size[/code] będzie typu [code]float[/code], otrzymamy błąd typów."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:39
msgid "Worse: due to dynamic typing, we won't get an error [i]right away[/i]. We will only get the error when calling [code]grid_to_world(Vector2(1, 1))[/code]."
msgstr "Co gorsza: z powodu dynamicznego typowania nie otrzymamy błędu [i]od razu[/i]. Pojawi się on dopiero w momencie wywołania [code]grid_to_world(Vector2(1, 1))[/code]."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:40
msgid "And that's a big problem."
msgstr "I to jest poważny problem."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:45
msgid "Because we're learning, we only have small code examples in this course. But your games' code will get long and split into many files. When coding, you often forget about the code you wrote several weeks ago."
msgstr "Ponieważ dopiero się uczymy, w tym kursie mamy tylko krótkie przykłady kodu. Jednak kod twoich gier będzie długi i podzielony na wiele plików. Podczas programowania często zapomina się o tym, co napisało się kilka tygodni wcześniej."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:46
msgid "And with a lot of code, it could take [i]hours[/i] of play before players trigger a type error in your code."
msgstr "A przy dużej ilości kodu może minąć nawet [i]wiele godzin[/i] rozgrywki, zanim gracze wywołają w nim błąd typów."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:45
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Using type hints"
msgstr "Używanie wskazówek typów"

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:53
msgid "Fortunately, GDScript has optional [i]type hints[/i]."
msgstr "Na szczęście GDScript oferuje opcjonalne wskazówki typu (ang. type hints)."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:54
msgid "Type hints let the computer know the value type you want for variables and report errors before running the code."
msgstr "Wskazówki typu pozwalają komputerowi wiedzieć, jaki typ wartości ma mieć zmienna, i zgłaszają błędy jeszcze przed uruchomieniem kodu."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:55
msgid "To specify the type a variable can accept, you can write a colon and a type after the name when defining a new variable."
msgstr "Aby określić typ, który zmienna może przyjmować, możesz napisać dwukropek i typ po nazwie zmiennej podczas jej definiowania."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:57
msgid "You could tell the computer you want [code]cell_size[/code] only to accept [code]Vector2[/code] values like so."
msgstr "Możesz powiedzieć komputerowi, że chcesz, aby [code]cell_size[/code] przyjmowało tylko wartości typu [code]Vector2[/code] w ten sposób."

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:61
msgid "If you try to replace the [code]cell_size[/code] with a value of another type later, the computer will not let you."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:65
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Letting the computer figure it out"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:71
msgid "GDScript comes with a feature called [i]type inference[/i]. In many cases, but not all, the computer can figure out the type of a variable for you."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:72
msgid "To do so, you write [code]:=[/code], without the type. The computer will set the type using the value after the equal sign. We could make [code]cell_size[/code] a variable of type [code]Vector2[/code] like so:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:75
msgid "This takes little typing, yet you get the benefits of using type hints, like the computer reporting errors better and faster."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:75
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Why bother to add hints?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:85
msgid "When you give the language hints like that, it will [i]prevent[/i] major type errors. When you work in Godot, you will see that the computer can report issues as you write the code. It makes the benefit even greater."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:86
msgid "Type hints can also help improve the readability of your code. It can help to put more information directly in the code. As we saw, types are essential when coding, and when using type hints, the computer will add them to the engine's built-in code documentation system."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:87
msgid "There's an incredible third benefit for you: by using type hints, you will learn types much faster. It's excellent for learning."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:88
msgid "In the following practices, you will write the correct type hints to make the code error-free."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Add the correct type hints to variables"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Our variables get the correct values but not the right hints. Using your type-fu, add the correct type names in the variable definitions."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "You need to write the type name between the colon and the equal sign."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Note: You cannot use type inference in this practice. You need to write the type name in full."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "Our variables have the wrong type hints, causing errors. Correct them to make the code run."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:105
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Fix the values to match the type hints"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:105
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "It is the other way around in this practice: the type hints are fine, but the values are not."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:105
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Your task is to fix the values after the equal sign, so they match the type hint of each variable."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:105
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "This time, it's the other way around: variables have the correct type hints but the wrong values. Change the values to make the code run."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:105
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "The type [code]float[/code] means decimal number, so you need to write a number with a decimal part, like [code]3.14[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:105
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "The type [code]int[/code] stands for integer or whole number, so you need the value to be a whole number without a decimal part."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-28-specifying-types/lesson.bbcode:105
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "The type [code]String[/code] means you need to write a text string, a value surrounded by quotes."
msgstr ""

msgid "Learn to Code From Zero with Godot"
msgstr ""
